3 SECTION 5. Chapter 27-20.5 of the North Dakota Century Code is created and enacted as
4 follows:
5 27 - 20.5 - 01. Definitions .
6 1. "Fitness to proceed" means sufficient present ability to consult with counsel and assist
7 in preparing the minor's defense with a reasonable degree of rational understanding or
8 a rational and factual understanding of the nature of the offense and delinquency
9 proceedings against the minor. A lack of fitness to proceed may result from the
10 presence of any condition, including mental illness, mental disorder, developmental
11 disability, or developmental immaturity.
12 2. "Minor" means an individual who is:
13 a. Under the age of eighteen years and is not married; or
14 b. Eighteen years of age or older with respect to a delinquent act committed while
15 under the age of eighteen years, and not married, unless an offense is
16 transferred under section 27 - 20.4 - 21 .
17 3. "Remediation" means the process of providing learning opportunities, services, and
18 support to achieve fitness to proceed.
19 4. "Remediation provider" means an individual providing remediation services for minors .
20 5. "Tier 1a mental health professional" is a psychiatrist licensed under chapter 43 - 17 or a
21 psychologist licensed under chapter 43 - 32 .
22 27 - 20.5 - 02. Age .
23 1. An individual under the age of ten years is deemed incapable of commission of an
24 offense defined by the constitution or statutes of this state.
25 2. An individual ten years of age or older may be assessed for mental fitness or capacity
26 under this chapter.
27 27 - 20.5 - 03. Motion for fitness to proceed examination .
28 1. If there is reason to doubt the minor's fitness to proceed, the court may order on its
29 own motion, or at the request of the minor, the minor's parent, legal guardian, legal
30 custodian, or attorney, or the prosecuting attorney, a fitness to proceed examination to
31 determine whether the minor is fit to proceed if the minor is the subject of a
