1 3. If the court orders a report to be open for the purpose of de-identified statistical
2 analysis, data gathering, or scientific study, the report must remain confidential.
3 4. Any incriminating statement made by a minor to the tier 1a mental health professiona l
4 as part of a fitness to proceed examination may not be used against the minor over
5 objection in any proceeding.
6 27 - 20.5 - 06. Fitness to proceed examination .
7 1. If there is reason to doubt the minor's fitness to proceed, the court shall order the
8 minor to be examined by a tier 1a mental health professional .
9 2. This section does not prohibit any party from retaining the party's own qualified tier 1a
10 mental health professional to conduct additional evaluations at the party's own
11 expense.
12 3. The fitness to proceed examination must be conducted in the least restrictive
13 environment and may not be conducted in a treatment facility as defined in section
14 25 - 03.1 - 02 .
15 4. The court shall order the prosecuting attorney, minor's attorney, and juvenile court staff
16 to submit any information considered relevant to the fitness to proceed examination to
17 the tier 1a mental health professional, including :
18 a. The names and addresses of all attorneys involved;
19 b. Information about the alleged offense; and
20 c. Any information about the minor's background which is in the prosecuting
21 attorney's possession.
22 5. Except as prohibited by federal law, the court shall require the attorneys and juvenile
23 court staff to provide any available records regarding the minor and any other
24 information relevant to the examination to the tier 1a mental health professional ,
25 including:
26 a. Psychiatric records;
27 b. School records;
28 c. Medical records; and
29 d. Child protective services records.
30 6. The requirement to provide records or information under subsections 4 and 5 does no t
31 limit, waive, or abrogate the work product doctrine or the attorney-client privilege, and
