11 missing or additional information within seventy-two hours upon discovery of the
12 missing information or receiving this information, and the attorneys and juvenile
13 court staff have seven days to send the information to the tier 1a mental health
14 professional.
15 8. A tier 1a mental health professional who conducts a fitness to proceed examination
16 shall submit a written report to the court no later than fifteen days from completing the
17 fitness to proceed examination. The report must include:
18 a. A description of the nature, content, and extent of the examination, including:
19 (1) A description of the assessment procedure, technique, and test used;
20 (2) Medical, educational, and court records reviewed; and
21 (3) Social, clinical, developmental, and available legal history.
22 b. A clinical assessment that includes:
23 (1) A mental status examination;
24 (2) The diagnosis and functional impact of mental illness, developmental
25 disability, or cognitive impairment. If the minor is taking medication, the
26 impact of the medication on the minor's mental state and behavior;
27 (3) An assessment of the minor's intelligence and maturity level, when relevant;
28 (4) The minor's age, developmental state, and decisionmaking abilities; and
29 (5) Whether the minor has any other factor that affects fitness to proceed.
30 c. A description of abilities and deficits in the following mental competency functions
31 related to the minor's fitness to proceed:
